Several JavaScript libraries support smooth, customizable scroll-to-top buttons:

- jQuery ScrollUp (jquery.scrollUp): Lightweight plugin with customizable text/icon, distance, speed, and animation.
  Example: $.scrollUp({ scrollText: 'Top', scrollSpeed: 500, animation: 'fade' });

- React Scroll To Top (react-scroll-to-top): Ready-made React component with props for smooth behavior, styling, and custom icon.
  Example: <ScrollToTop smooth color="#fff" style={{ background: '#333' }} />

- GSAP ScrollToPlugin: Framework-agnostic, highly smooth scrolling; you wire up your own button.
  Example: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollToPlugin); gsap.to(window, { duration: 0.6, scrollTo: 0, ease: 'power2.out' });

- Smooth Scroll (cferdinandi/smooth-scroll): Vanilla JS smooth scrolling; can animate to top programmatically.
  Example: const scroll = new SmoothScroll(); scroll.animateScroll(0);

- React Scroll Up (react-scroll-up or react-scroll-up-button): React components offering show-on-scroll and customizable animations.

ProgressBar.js is one of the easiest libraries for animated circular progress with numbers. It’s lightweight, vanilla JS, and supports circle/line/semicircle shapes with built-in animation.

Quick example:
1) Install: npm i progressbar.js
2) HTML: <div id="circle"></div>
3) JS:
import ProgressBar from 'progressbar.js';
const bar = new ProgressBar.Circle('#circle', {
  strokeWidth: 6,
  trailWidth: 6,
  duration: 1200,
  easing: 'easeInOut'
});
bar.animate(0.75, {
  step: (_, circle) => circle.setText(Math.round(circle.value()*100) + '%')
});

Alternatives:
- jquery-circle-progress: Simple if you already use jQuery.
- Easy Pie Chart (jQuery): Minimal and easy for basic circles.
- Chart.js (Doughnut): More flexible charts; can style as a progress ring.
- Gauge.js: Good for gauge-style circular indicators.
- Anime.js + SVG: Very flexible if you want custom SVG paths (more manual).

